Traditional equity trade
* Buy shares once
* Sell shares once
* Profit/loss depends only on entry & exit

Problem for banks & clients
Clients want regular accumulation
Want discounted buying
Want structured risk
Want automation over time

➡️ Result: Structured Products

STRUCTURED PRODUCT (SP) -->
A contract that combines derivatives + rules + lifecycle events
It is:
Long-running (weeks/months)
Event-driven
Rule-based
Heavy on valuation, accrual, fixing, maturity
* Accumulator / Decumulator is one type of SP.


Accumulator = agreement to buy shares every working day at a fixed price
Not optional
Not one-time
Obligatory & repeated

Real-life analogy
Imagine:
You promise to buy 10 apples daily
Price fixed at ₹50
Market price keeps changing
You must buy anyway
That’s an Accumulator.

Decumulator --> Agreement to sell shares every working day at a fixed price

| Term         | Meaning                    |
| ------------ | -------------------------- |
| Underlying   | The share (e.g. Apple)     |
| Strike Price | Fixed agreed price         |
| Market Price | Today’s live price         |
| Daily Units  | Units per day              |
| Accrual      | Daily obligation recording |
| Fixing       | Settlement checkpoint      |
| Knock-out    | Early termination trigger  |
| Maturity     | Natural end of contract    |

Every working day (COB):
System reads market price
Compares with strike
Calculates accrued units
Updates:ACCRUED.UNITS1


Example
Strike = 50
Market = 45
Daily Units = 100
The customer must buy 100 shares at 50, even though the market is 45
➡️ Customer is at a loss

GEARING (RISK MULTIPLIER) --> “If market goes against you, buy MORE shares”
This is Gearing Factor
Example
Daily Units = 100
Gearing = 2
Market < Strike
➡️ Accrued Units = 200

KNOCK-IN & KNOCK-OUT -->
Knock-In
Accrual starts only after price touches a level

Knock-Out
Contract terminates early
No more accrual
Final settlement triggered

Example
Knock-out = 60
Market hits 60
➡️ Contract ends

Example (Knock-In)
Product setup
Underlying: ABC Stock
Strike: 50
Knock-In level: 55
Accrual: 1 unit per day
Tenor: 10 days

| Day   | Market Price | Accrual               |
| ----- | ------------ | --------------------- |
| Day 1 | 52           | ❌ No (not knocked-in) |
| Day 2 | 54           | ❌ No                  |
| Day 3 | **55**       | ✅ Knock-In triggered  |
| Day 4 | 56           | ✅ 1 unit              |
| Day 5 | 57           | ✅ 1 unit              |

2️⃣ Knock-Out (KO)
Meaning:
👉 If price hits the KO level, the contract ends immediately.

No more accrual.
Settlement happens early.

Example (Knock-Out)
Product setup
Knock-Out level: 60
Accrual per day: 1 unit

| Day   | Market Price | Accrual      |
| ----- | ------------ | ------------ |
| Day 1 | 56           | +1           |
| Day 2 | 58           | +1           |
| Day 3 | **60**       | 🚨 Knock-Out |




FIXING -->
Fixing = periodic settlement checkpoint
“Okay, enough accrual — now settle”

What happens in Fixing?
Accrued units are:
Exercised
Settled (cash / shares)
Residual option expires

Status updated:
FIXED = YES
Each fixing period:
Stored as multi-value set
Cannot be edited after fixing

Why fixing exists?
Avoid waiting till maturity
Reduce risk
Allow partial settlement

Example — Accrual Product WITH Fixing
Product setup
Accrual: 1 unit per valid day
Fixing frequency: Monthly
Tenor: 3 months
| Day      | Accrual  |
| -------- | -------- |
| Day 1–20 | 20 units |


📍 Fixing Date (End of Month 1)
✔ 20 units are:
Exercised
Settled (cash/shares)

Month 2
| Day      | Accrual  |
| -------- | -------- |
| Day 1–18 | 18 units |


Month 3
Same logic again.

Fixing 1 → 20 units → FIXED = YES
Fixing 2 → 18 units → FIXED = YES
Fixing 3 → 22 units → FIXED = YES

With fixing:
✅ Partial settlement
✅ Risk reduced over time
✅ Cash flows earlier


🔰 LEVEL 9 — UNWIND (EARLY EXIT)
Client can exit:
Fully
Partially

Full Unwind
Contract closed
No future accrual

Partial Unwind
Daily units reduced
Accrual continues on reduced quantity

📌 Important:
Unwind effective date matters
Back-dated unwind needs manual corrections

NOVATION (TRANSFER OF CONTRACT)
What is novation?
Moving the contract from one party to another

Types:
Internal: Client A → Client B (same bank)
External: Client → outside entity
Optional fees apply.


